syntactic constructions to lexical and grammatical elements designed to hook on to features outside the clause in the interactional context. The book offers a focused treatment of the general nature of linguistic indexicality in the larger perspective of the semiotics of language, including examinations of domain-straddling indexical functions. It presents studies of the role of indexicality in synchrony and diachrony with descriptive cases from a number of languages from diverse language families and it examines the way indexicality enters into the mechanisms of change, including examinations of semiotic shifts from indexical to symbolic function and vice versa. The book is relevant for researchers and students in historical and synchronic linguistics from a variety of linguistic frameworks with an interest in the role of semiotics in linguistic analysis.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aIndexikalität. 4aSemiotik. 4aSprachwandel. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Historical & Comparative.2bisacsh  aIndexicality in Language.  aLanguage Change.  aPrinciples of Linguistic Analysis.  aSemiotics of Linguistic Structure.1 aAndersen, Henning, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiewald, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaeta, Livio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeltoft, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensen, Eva Skafte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMasini, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMauri, Caterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNemo, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu